## Why 360° camera is especially useful

The user has access to a 360° camera. This is highly relevant.

Normal photos are strongly direction-dependent:

```text
same point + different direction = different visual composition
```

A 360° panorama gives a more complete observation around a point.

Advantages:

- reduced direction bias,
- full visual context around an observation point,
- better approximation of what is visible from a place,
- possible split into directional sectors,
- possible front/back/left/right statistics,
- possible azimuth-based analysis.

A 360° image can be processed in several ways:

```text
1. Full panorama analysis
   Calculate class percentages for the whole panorama.

2. Sector analysis
   Split panorama into sectors, e.g. 4, 8 or 12 directions.

3. Directional samples
   Extract perspective views from selected azimuths and process them like normal images.

4. Route-based analysis
   Use camera path and direction to aggregate visual statistics along streets or trails.
```

Example sector output:

```text
point_id
azimuth_start
azimuth_end
vegetation_percent
road_percent
building_percent
sky_percent
sidewalk_percent
```

This would be more GIS-useful than one single number per point.

